== Tips and Tricks == <!--T:17-->

=== Using Vim like ex or ed from the command line === <!--T:18-->

<!--T:19-->
It is possible to use Vim for one-liners â€” commands that can be used in scripts or on the command line to make changes in an unattended manner.

<!--T:20-->
For instance, the following command adds <code>#</code> to the beginning of each line in the {{Path|file.txt}} file:

<!--T:21-->
{{Cmd|vim -c ":%s/^/#/g" -c ":x" file.txt}}

<!--T:22-->
What happens is that Vim interprets the passed on commands (through the <code>-c</code> option). The first command is Vim's substitution command (which is very similar to <tt>sed</tt>'s), the second one is Vim's instruction to save and exit the editor.

=== Change file encoding === <!--T:23-->

<!--T:24-->
To change the file encoding of a file to [[UTF-8]], use the following command (in Vim command mode):

<!--T:25-->
{{Cmd|e ++enc{{=}}utf8|prompt=:|color=orange}}

<!--T:26-->
As shown in the previous trick, it is possible to do this from the command line as well:

<!--T:27-->
{{Cmd|vim -c ":wq! ++enc{{=}}utf8" file.txt}}

